With this polarized nuclear imaging framework, we can perform both emission and transmission tomography simultaneously.However, to make this practical, we need suitable polarized radioisotopes, or tracers.

This table lists a few existing candidates — isotopes of xenon and krypton — that can, in principle, be polarized and used for such imaging.For example, xenon-131m has a half-life of about twelve days and a gamma emission energy around one hundred sixty-four kilo–electron volts.Xenon-127m decays faster — with a half-life of sixty-nine seconds, emitting gamma rays between one hundred twenty-five and one hundred seventy kilo–electron volts.
And krypton-79m has a half-life of about fifty seconds, with gamma emission near one hundred thirty kilo–electron volts.
